definition.value: Any indole alkaloid obtained by the oxidative coupling two indole nuclei at the beta-position. Found commonly in the plants of the family calycanthaceae.
Any alkylbenzene that is benzene substituted with one or more methyl groups.
A  monocyclic arene that is benzene substituted with one or more alkyl groups.
Any methylbenzene that is benzene substituted by four methyl groups at unspecified positions.
A tetramethylbenzene carrying methyl groups at positions 1, 2, 4 and 5.
The species :BR containing an electrically neutral univalent boron atom with two formally non-bonding electrons.

An organic thiophosphate that is N-methyl-2-[(2-sulfanylethyl)sulfanyl]propanamide in which the thiol group has been converted into the corresponding O,O-dimethyl thiophoshate. Formerly used as an insecticide and acaricide, it is no longer approved for use within the European Union.
Any aromatic carboxylic acid that is anthracene substituted by a carboxy group at unspecified position.
A tetramethylbenzene that consists of benzene substituted by methyl groups at positions 1, 2, 3 and 4.
A methylbenzene that is benzene in which five of the hydrogens are replaced by methyl groups.
A germacranolide with anthelminthic, antiparasitic and antiviral activities.
A methylbenzene that is benzene in which all six hydrogens have been replaced by methyl groups.
A Good's buffer substance, pKa = 6.15 at 20 degreeC.

A synthetic peptide that is identical to the 24-amino acid segment at the N-terminal of adrenocorticotropic hormone (corticotropin). A segment similar in all species, it contains the biological activity that stimulates production of corticosteroids in the adrenal cortex. It is used diagnostically to investigate adrenocortical insufficiency.
